37/*
38 * Data types corresponding to multi-byte integral values within data
39 * structures. These are defined as arrays of octets, so that they're
40 * not aligned on their "natural" boundaries, and so that you *must*
41 * use the EXTRACT_ macros to extract them (which you should be doing
42 * *anyway*, so as not to assume a particular byte order or alignment
43 * in your code).
44 */
45typedef unsigned char nd_uint16_t[2];
46typedef unsigned char nd_uint24_t[3];
47typedef unsigned char nd_uint32_t[4];
48typedef unsigned char nd_uint40_t[5];
49typedef unsigned char nd_uint48_t[6];
50typedef unsigned char nd_uint56_t[7];
51typedef unsigned char nd_uint64_t[8];
52
53/*
54 * Use this for IPv4 addresses. It's defined as an array of octets, so
55 * that it's not aligned on its "natural" boundary, and it's defined as
56 * a structure in the hopes that this makes it harder to naively use
57 * EXTRACT_32BITS() to extract the value - in many cases you just want
58 * to use UNALIGNED_MEMCPY() to copy its value, so that it remains in
59 * network byte order.
60 */
61typedef struct {
62 unsigned char bytes[4];
63} nd_ipv4;
64
65/*
66 * Data types corresponding to single-byte integral values, for
67 * completeness.
68 */
69typedef unsigned char nd_uint8_t;
70typedef signed char nd_int8_t;

142struct netdissect_options {
143 int ndo_bflag; /* print 4 byte ASes in ASDOT notation */
144 int ndo_eflag; /* print ethernet header */
145 int ndo_fflag; /* don't translate "foreign" IP address */
146 int ndo_Kflag; /* don't check TCP checksums */
147 int ndo_nflag; /* leave addresses as numbers */
148 int ndo_Nflag; /* remove domains from printed host names */
149 int ndo_qflag; /* quick (shorter) output */
150 int ndo_Sflag; /* print raw TCP sequence numbers */
151 int ndo_tflag; /* print packet arrival time */
152 int ndo_uflag; /* Print undecoded NFS handles */
153 int ndo_vflag; /* verbosity level */
154 int ndo_xflag; /* print packet in hex */
155 int ndo_Xflag; /* print packet in hex/ascii */
156 int ndo_Aflag; /* print packet only in ascii observing TAB,
157 * LF, CR and SPACE as graphical chars
158 */
159 int ndo_Hflag; /* dissect 802.11s draft mesh standard */
160 int ndo_packet_number; /* print a packet number in the beginning of line */
161 int ndo_suppress_default_print; /* don't use default_print() for unknown packet types */
162 int ndo_tstamp_precision; /* requested time stamp precision */
163 const char *program_name; /* Name of the program using the library */
164
165 char *ndo_espsecret;
166 struct sa_list *ndo_sa_list_head; /* used by print-esp.c */
167 struct sa_list *ndo_sa_default;
168
169 char *ndo_sigsecret; /* Signature verification secret key */
170
171 int ndo_packettype; /* as specified by -T */
172
173 int ndo_snaplen;
174
175 /*global pointers to beginning and end of current packet (during printing) */
176 const u_char *ndo_packetp;
177 const u_char *ndo_snapend;
178
179 /* pointer to the if_printer function */
180 if_printer ndo_if_printer;
181
182 /* pointer to void function to output stuff */
183 void (*ndo_default_print)(netdissect_options *,
184 register const u_char *bp, register u_int length);
185
186 /* pointer to function to do regular output */
187 int (*ndo_printf)(netdissect_options *,
188 const char *fmt, ...)
189#ifdef __ATTRIBUTE___FORMAT_OK_FOR_FUNCTION_POINTERS
190 __attribute__ ((format (printf, 2, 3)))
191#endif
192 ;
193 /* pointer to function to output errors */
194 void (*ndo_error)(netdissect_options *,
195 const char *fmt, ...)
196#ifdef __ATTRIBUTE___NORETURN_OK_FOR_FUNCTION_POINTERS
197 __attribute__ ((noreturn))
198#endif /* __ATTRIBUTE___NORETURN_OK_FOR_FUNCTION_POINTERS */
199#ifdef __ATTRIBUTE___FORMAT_OK_FOR_FUNCTION_POINTERS
200 __attribute__ ((format (printf, 2, 3)))
201#endif /* __ATTRIBUTE___FORMAT_OK_FOR_FUNCTION_POINTERS */
202 ;
203 /* pointer to function to output warnings */
204 void (*ndo_warning)(netdissect_options *,
205 const char *fmt, ...)
206#ifdef __ATTRIBUTE___FORMAT_OK_FOR_FUNCTION_POINTERS
207 __attribute__ ((format (printf, 2, 3)))
208#endif
209 ;
210};

240/*
241 * Maximum snapshot length. This should be enough to capture the full
242 * packet on most network interfaces.
243 *
244 *
245 * Somewhat arbitrary, but chosen to be:
246 *
247 * 1) big enough for maximum-size Linux loopback packets (65549)
248 * and some USB packets captured with USBPcap:
249 *
250 * http://desowin.org/usbpcap/
251 *
252 * (> 131072, < 262144)
253 *
254 * and
255 *
256 * 2) small enough not to cause attempts to allocate huge amounts of
257 * memory; some applications might use the snapshot length in a
258 * savefile header to control the size of the buffer they allocate,
259 * so a size of, say, 2^31-1 might not work well.
260 *
261 * XXX - does it need to be bigger still?
262 */
263#define MAXIMUM_SNAPLEN 262144
264
265/*
266 * The default snapshot length is the maximum.
267 */
268#define DEFAULT_SNAPLEN MAXIMUM_SNAPLEN

275#define NTOHS(x) (x) = ntohs(x)

277#define HTONS(x) (x) = htons(x)

280/*
281 * True if "l" bytes of "var" were captured.
282 *
283 * The "ndo->ndo_snapend - (l) <= ndo->ndo_snapend" checks to make sure
284 * "l" isn't so large that "ndo->ndo_snapend - (l)" underflows.
285 *
286 * The check is for <= rather than < because "l" might be 0.
287 *
288 * We cast the pointers to uintptr_t to make sure that the compiler
289 * doesn't optimize away any of these tests (which it is allowed to
290 * do, as adding an integer to, or subtracting an integer from, a
291 * pointer assumes that the pointer is a pointer to an element of an
292 * array and that the result of the addition or subtraction yields a
293 * pointer to another member of the array, so that, for example, if
294 * you subtract a positive integer from a pointer, the result is
295 * guaranteed to be less than the original pointer value). See
296 *
297 * http://www.kb.cert.org/vuls/id/162289
298 */
299
300/*
301 * Test in two parts to avoid these warnings:
302 * comparison of unsigned expression >= 0 is always true [-Wtype-limits],
303 * comparison is always true due to limited range of data type [-Wtype-limits].
304 */
305#define IS_NOT_NEGATIVE(x) (((x) > 0) || ((x) == 0))
306
307#define ND_TTEST2(var, l) \
308 (IS_NOT_NEGATIVE(l) && \
309 ((uintptr_t)ndo->ndo_snapend - (l) <= (uintptr_t)ndo->ndo_snapend && \
310 (uintptr_t)&(var) <= (uintptr_t)ndo->ndo_snapend - (l)))
311
312/* True if "var" was captured */
313#define ND_TTEST(var) ND_TTEST2(var, sizeof(var))
314
315/* Bail if "l" bytes of "var" were not captured */
316#define ND_TCHECK2(var, l) if (!ND_TTEST2(var, l)) goto trunc
317
318/* Bail if "var" was not captured */
319#define ND_TCHECK(var) ND_TCHECK2(var, sizeof(var))
320
321#define ND_PRINT(STUFF) (*ndo->ndo_printf)STUFF
322#define ND_DEFAULTPRINT(ap, length) (*ndo->ndo_default_print)(ndo, ap, length)

342/*
343 * Locale-independent macros for testing character properties and
344 * stripping the 8th bit from characters. Assumed to be handed
345 * a value between 0 and 255, i.e. don't hand them a char, as
346 * those might be in the range -128 to 127.
347 */
348#define ND_ISASCII(c) (!((c) & 0x80)) /* value is an ASCII code point */
349#define ND_ISPRINT(c) ((c) >= 0x20 && (c) <= 0x7E)
350#define ND_ISGRAPH(c) ((c) > 0x20 && (c) <= 0x7E)
351#define ND_TOASCII(c) ((c) & 0x7F)

356#ifdef LBL_ALIGN
357/*
358 * The processor doesn't natively handle unaligned loads,
359 * and the compiler might "helpfully" optimize memcpy()
360 * and memcmp(), when handed pointers that would normally
361 * be properly aligned, into sequences that assume proper
362 * alignment.
363 *
364 * Do copies and compares of possibly-unaligned data by
365 * calling routines that wrap memcpy() and memcmp(), to
366 * prevent that optimization.
367 */
368extern void unaligned_memcpy(void *, const void *, size_t);
369extern int unaligned_memcmp(const void *, const void *, size_t);
370#define UNALIGNED_MEMCPY(p, q, l) unaligned_memcpy((p), (q), (l))
371#define UNALIGNED_MEMCMP(p, q, l) unaligned_memcmp((p), (q), (l))
372#else
373/*
374 * The procesor natively handles unaligned loads, so just use memcpy()
375 * and memcmp(), to enable those optimizations.
376 */
377#define UNALIGNED_MEMCPY(p, q, l) memcpy((p), (q), (l))
378#define UNALIGNED_MEMCMP(p, q, l) memcmp((p), (q), (l))
379#endif

448/*
449 * Structure passed to some printers to allow them to print
450 * link-layer address information if ndo_eflag isn't set
451 * (because they are for protocols that don't have their
452 * own addresses, so that we'd want to report link-layer
453 * address information).
454 *
455 * This contains a pointer to an address and a pointer to a routine
456 * to which we pass that pointer in order to get a string.
457 */
458struct lladdr_info {
459 const char *(*addr_string)(netdissect_options *, const u_char *);
460 const u_char *addr;
461};
